President Barack Obama has proclaimed September 2016 as National Preparedness Month in the United States. He emphasizes the importance of being prepared for emergencies and encourages individuals, families, and communities to take proactive steps to improve their readiness. This includes signing up for local alerts, checking insurance coverage, documenting valuables, creating an emergency communication and evacuation plan, and having a fully stocked disaster supply kit. Businesses are also urged to prepare their employees and develop a business continuity plan. The President emphasizes the need for leaders to address vulnerabilities highlighted in the 2016 National Preparedness Report and for all Americans to participate in preparedness activities. He also mentions the importance of addressing the risks associated with climate change and investing in infrastructure to improve response and recovery efforts. The President pays tribute to those who respond to disasters and calls on Americans to do their part in protecting themselves and helping others.